## Pull Request Review: SRCH003 - Search Bar Placeholder Cycling

### Summary

The implementation adds a cycling placeholder overlay to the search bar using a custom hook (`useCyclingPlaceholder`), a positioned `<span>` overlay, and CSS opacity transitions. The approach is sound overall, but there are several issues ranging from a timing bug to a referential identity problem that will cause the hook to malfunction in production.

---

### CRITICAL - Referential Identity Causes Effect to Re-fire on Every Render

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/search_bar/search_bar.tsx`, line 55-58

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  // ...
}, [
  placeholders,  // <-- array reference
  isActive,
]);
```

The `placeholders` dependency is the `cyclingPlaceholders` prop, which in `root_search_view.tsx` is a module-level constant (`CYCLING_PLACEHOLDERS`). This works **today** because the constant has a stable reference. However, the hook's contract is fragile -- if any consumer ever passes an inline array literal (e.g., `cyclingPlaceholders={['a', 'b']}`), the effect will tear down and re-create the interval on every single render, resetting the cycle index to 0 and never actually cycling.

**Recommendation:** Either:
- Accept a ref or memoize inside the hook using a shallow array comparison
- Document this constraint with a JSDoc on the `cyclingPlaceholders` prop
- Or, more robustly, store the placeholders in a ref inside the hook and only reset the effect when the array contents actually change:

```tsx
const placeholdersRef = useRef(placeholders);
const didChange = !placeholders || !placeholdersRef.current ||
  placeholders.length !== placeholdersRef.current.length ||
  placeholders.some((p, i) => p !== placeholdersRef.current![i]);

if (didChange) {
  placeholdersRef.current = placeholders;
}

useEffect(() => {
  // use placeholdersRef.current
}, [didChange, isActive]);
```

**Severity:** Critical (latent bug). Currently masked by the module-level constant but will break the moment anyone refactors.

---

### BUG - FADE_DURATION vs $transition-slow Mismatch

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/search_bar/search_bar.tsx`, line 23-24

```tsx
const FADE_DURATION = 300;
```

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/search_bar/search_bar.scss`, line 96

```scss
transition: opacity #{$transition-slow} ease;
```

`$transition-slow` resolves to `250ms`, but `FADE_DURATION` in JS is `300ms`. The text swap happens at 300ms, but the CSS transition completes at 250ms. This means:

- The text changes 50ms **after** the fade-out animation finishes, during which the old text is fully invisible but still rendered.
- When `setVisible(true)` fires, the new text appears and then fades in over 250ms. This part works, but the delay before the swap is perceptible as a stutter.

These values **must** be synchronized. The JS constant should equal or be slightly less than the CSS duration. The cleanest fix: use the same 250ms value in JS, or better, define a single source of truth (e.g., a CSS custom property read from JS, or a shared constant exported from a tokens file).

**Severity:** Medium (visual glitch -- 50ms blank gap between fade-out end and text swap).

---

### ISSUE - No Index Reset When `placeholders` Array Changes

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/search_bar/search_bar.tsx`, lines 36-39

```tsx
if (!placeholders || placeholders.length <= 1 || !isActive) {
  setIndex(0);
  setVisible(true);
  return;
}
```

When the effect runs because `placeholders` changed (e.g., different view providing different placeholders), the index is only reset if the new array has 0-1 items or `isActive` is false. If a new array of the same or greater length is provided while `isActive` is true, the `index` state carries over. This could display placeholder text from the wrong position in the new array if the previous index exceeds the new array length.

The `% placeholders.length` guard on line 68 prevents an out-of-bounds crash, but the user could momentarily see the wrong placeholder (e.g., index 3 in a new 4-item array starting from the 4th item instead of the 1st).

**Recommendation:** Add `setIndex(0)` at the top of the effect unconditionally, or at least when the placeholders reference changes.

**Severity:** Low (edge case, but sloppy).

---

### STYLE - Cycling Placeholder Vertical Alignment May Drift from Input Text

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/search_bar/search_bar.scss`, lines 84-101

```scss
.search-bar__cycling-placeholder {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  height: 100%;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  font-family: $font-family;
  font-size: $font-search;
  color: var(--text-400);
  pointer-events: none;
  // ...
}
```

The overlay uses `display: flex; align-items: center` on the full height of the wrapper. The `<input>` element uses `height: 100%` with no explicit `line-height` or padding. On most browsers, input text is vertically centered by default, so this will likely match. However, the alignment is coincidental rather than guaranteed -- different browsers and OS font rendering may place the input text baseline at a slightly different position than a flex-centered span.

**Recommendation:** Consider adding explicit `line-height` and `padding` to both the input and the cycling placeholder to guarantee pixel-perfect alignment, or test across target platforms to confirm. Since this is a Tauri app (primarily WebKit/Chromium), the risk is lower but worth verifying.

**Severity:** Low (cosmetic, may not manifest).

---

### GOOD - Proper Cleanup on Unmount

The cleanup function on lines 51-54 correctly clears both the interval and the pending timeout:

```tsx
return () => {
  clearInterval(interval);
  clearTimeout(timeout);
};
```

This handles the unmount-mid-transition case correctly. If the component unmounts between `setVisible(false)` and the timeout firing, the timeout is cleared and no state update on an unmounted component occurs. React 18+ handles this gracefully anyway, but the cleanup is still proper hygiene.

---

### GOOD - Accessibility

- `aria-hidden="true"` on the cycling placeholder span (line 199) correctly hides the decorative overlay from screen readers.
- The input retains `aria-label="Search commands"` (line 192), so screen readers have a meaningful label regardless of the visual placeholder.
- The native `placeholder` attribute is correctly removed when cycling is active (`hasCycling ? undefined : placeholder` on line 187), avoiding a double-text visual artifact.

---

### GOOD - pointer-events: none

The overlay span has `pointer-events: none` (line 94 in SCSS), ensuring clicks pass through to the input. Users can click anywhere in the search bar to focus the input even when the cycling placeholder is displayed.

---

### MINOR - className Construction

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/search_bar/search_bar.tsx`, line 198

```tsx
className={`search-bar__cycling-placeholder${cycling.visible ? '' : ' search-bar__cycling-placeholder--hidden'}`}
```

This works but is a long string interpolation. Consider a utility or at minimum a `const` for readability, especially since the project doesn't use a classnames library. Not a blocker.

---

### SUMMARY

| Issue | Severity | Verdict |
|-------|----------|---------|
